This paper introduces **Evolving the Proxy Search Space (EPS)**, a novel approach built upon RandomNAS. The method aims to identify an effective proxy search space (PS)—a small, high-quality subset of the global search space (GS)—thereby significantly improving the search efficiency of RandomNAS while preserving strong correlation with top-performing architectures. EPS operates iteratively in three stages:  
1. Training the supernet by randomly sampling architectures from the PS;  
2. Validating architectures in the PS on a held-out validation subset during training intervals;  
3. Evolving the PS via a tournament selection evolutionary algorithm enhanced with an aging mechanism.

The paper is well-structured and presents a coherent narrative. The core idea of efficiently sampling from a refined search space is compelling, and the goal of autonomously constructing the search space through search strategies is noteworthy. However, the methodological contribution appears somewhat incremental, as EPS (Algorithm 1) closely mirrors the aging evolution strategy introduced by Real et al. (2018, 2019). Here, the same search strategy is repurposed to dynamically and iteratively build the proxy search space itself.

It is important to recognize that multiple existing search strategies—such as (1) random search, (2) evolutionary algorithms (Real et al., 2018), and (3) progressive decision processes (PNAS; Liu et al., 2018)—could in principle be adapted to derive a proxy search space. While random sampling from the GS aligns with random search, EPS specifically adopts an evolutionary approach for search space construction. One could even envision employing progressive NAS algorithms to establish a proxy search space. A comparative analysis of how different proxy search spaces affect search efficiency would help clarify the novelty of EPS and strengthen the paper’s overall contribution.
